    • Method Detail

      • numericalValueOf

        public static Number numericalValueOf(String s)
        Returns the numerical value of the string s, or null if s does not have a numerical value.

        If s is a valid Lua integer literal with optional sign, the numerical value is the corresponding integer; if s is a valid Lua float literal with optional sign, the numerical value is the corresponding float. Otherwise, the s does not have a numerical value.

        Leading and trailing whitespace in s is ignored by this method.

        Numbers returned by this method are in the canonical representation.

        Parameters:
        s - string to convert to numerical value, may be null
        Returns:
        a number representing the numerical value of s (in the canonical representation), or null if s does not have a numerical value

      • numericalValueOf

        public static Number numericalValueOf(Object o)
        Returns the numerical value of the object o, or null if o does not have a numerical value.

        If o is already a number, returns o cast to number. If o is a string, returns its numerical value (see numericalValueOf(String)). Otherwise, returns null.

        This method differs from arithmeticValueOf(Object) in that it preserves the numerical value representation of coerced strings. For use in arithmetic operations following Lua's argument conversion rules, use that method instead.

        Numbers returned by this method are not necessarily in the canonical representation.

        Parameters:
        o - object to convert to numerical value, may be null
        Returns:
        number representing the numerical value of o (not necessarily in the canonical representation), of null if o does not have a numerical value
        See Also:
        arithmeticValueOf(Object)

      • toNumericalValue

        public static Number toNumericalValue(Object o,
                                      String name)
        Returns the numerical value of o, throwing a ConversionException if o does not have a numerical value.

        The conversion rules are those of numericalValueOf(Object); the only difference is that this method throws an exception rather than returning null to signal errors.

        Numbers returned by this method are not necessarily in the canonical representation.

        Parameters:
        o - object to convert to numerical value, may be null
        name - value name for error reporting, may be null
        Returns:
        number representing the numerical value of o (not necessarily in the canonical representation), guaranteed to be non-null
        Throws:
        ConversionException - if o is not a number or string convertible to number.
        See Also:
        numericalValueOf(Object)

        If n has an integer value i, returns the canonical representation of i; otherwise, returns the canonical representation of n (see toCanonicalNumber(Number)).

        Throws:

        If o is a number, returns the number normalised (see normaliseKey(Number). Otherwise, returns o.

        Parameters:

        Returns:
        normalised number if o is a number, o otherwise

      • arithmeticValueOf

        public static Number arithmeticValueOf(Object o)
        Returns the arithmetic value of the object o, or null if o does not have an arithmetic value.

        If o is a number, then that number is its arithmetic value. If o is a string that has a numerical value (see numericalValueOf(String)), its arithmetic value is the numerical value converted to a float. Otherwise, o does not have an arithmetic value.

        Note that this method differs from numericalValueOf(Object) in that it coerces strings convertible to numbers into into floats rather than preserving their numerical value representation, and also note that this conversion happens after the numerical value has been determined. Most significantly,

             Conversions.arithmeticValueOf("-0")

        yields 0.0 rather than 0 (as would be the case with numericalValueOf("-0")), or -0.0 (it would in the case if the string was parsed directly as a float).

        Numbers returned by this method are not necessarily in the canonical representation.

        Parameters:
        o - object to convert to arithmetic value, may be null
        Returns:
        number representing the arithmetic value of o (not necessarily in the canonical representation), or null if o does not have an arithmetic value
        See Also:
        numericalValueOf(Object)

      • integerValueOf

        public static Long integerValueOf(Number n)
        Returns the integer value of the number n, or null if n does not have an integer value.

        n has an integer value if and only if the number it denotes can be represented as a signed 64-bit integer. That integer is then the integer value of n. In other words, if n is a float, it has an integer value if and only if it can be converted to a long without loss of precision.

        Parameters:
        n - number to convert to integer, must not be null
        Returns:
        a Long representing the integer value of n, or null if n does not have an integer value
        Throws:
        NullPointerException - if n is null
        See Also:
        LuaMathOperators.hasExactIntegerRepresentation(double)

      • toIntegerValue

        public static long toIntegerValue(Number n)
        Returns the integer value of the number n, throwing a NoIntegerRepresentationException if n does not have an integer value.

        This is a variant of integerValueOf(Number); the difference is that this method throws an exception rather than returning null to signal that n does not have an integer value, and that this method returns the unboxed integer value of n (as a long).

        Parameters:
        n - object to be converted to integer, must not be null
        Returns:
        integer value of n
        Throws:
        NoIntegerRepresentationException - if n does not have an integer value
        NullPointerException - if n is null

      • stringValueOf

        public static String stringValueOf(Number n)
        Returns the string value of the number n.

        The string value of integers is the result of LuaFormat.toString(long) on their numerical value; similarly the string value of floats is the result of LuaFormat.toString(double) on their numerical value.

        Parameters:

        Returns:
        string value of n, guaranteed to be non-null
        Throws:
        NullPointerException - if n is null

      • stringValueOf

        public static String stringValueOf(Object o)
        Returns the string value of the object o, or null if o does not have a string value.

        If o is a string, that is the string value. If o is a number, returns the string value of that number (see stringValueOf(Number)). Otherwise, o does not have a string value.

        Parameters:
        o - object to be converted to string, may be null
        Returns:
        string value of o, or null if o does not have a string value

      • toHumanReadableString

        public static String toHumanReadableString(Object o)
        Converts the object o to a human-readable string format.

        The conversion rules are the following:

        • If o is a string or number, returns the string value of o;
        • if o is nil (i.e., null), returns "nil";
        • if o is a boolean, returns "true" if o is true or "false" if o is false;
        • otherwise, returns the string of the form "TYPE: 0xHASH", where TYPE is the Lua type of o, and HASH is the Object.hashCode() of o in hexadecimal format.

        Note that this method ignores the object's toString() method and its __tostring metamethod.

        Parameters:
        o - the object to be converted to string, may be null
        Returns:
        human-readable string representation of o
        See Also:
        stringValueOf(Object)

      • toErrorObject

        public static Object toErrorObject(Throwable t)
        Converts a Throwable t to an error object.

        If t is a LuaRuntimeException, the result of this operation is the result of its LuaRuntimeException.getErrorObject(). Otherwise, the result is Throwable.getMessage().

        Parameters:
        t - throwable to convert to error object, must not be null
        Returns:
        error object represented by t
        Throws:
        NullPointerException - if t is null
